`new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;(5)` creates a new __empty__ list with initial capacity 5, which isn&#39;t at all what you want. What you wanted was:

```
var list = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();
list.add(5);
```

Or possibly if you want to one-liner it `new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;(List.of(5))`.

More generally this concept (&#39;map a key to a list of values; create the list upon inserting the first value and add to an existing list otherwise&#39;) comes a ton, and there&#39;s a nicer way to do it:

```
Map&lt;Integer, ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

map.computeIfAbsent(col, k -&gt; new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;()).add(n.val);
```

As the name suggests, `computeIfAbsent` will run the provided lambda (the stuff after the arrow) __only__ if key `col` is absent (is not in the map at all). In this case, it runs the code, and sets it as the value to go with key `col`. The method call itself (`computeIfAbsent`) returns the generated value if that happened, or the existing value if that happened. Either way, that&#39;s the list you want to add to. Hence, one line, no need for `if` shenanigans.

