I guess the issue was resolved. Posting a solution for anyone&#39;s future references.

The issue that I can see with this is while creating S3Presigner instance you are not actually providing the credentials.

    presigner = S3Presigner.create();

If you create presigner instance using this approach, in reality what it actually do is go through all the possible ways of creating presigner instance. For example one of the approach would be to create using IAM role, one would be get the credentials from the config and many more. But it can fail if these are not done correctly. For a better approach what we can do is to create the presigner instance similar to creating S3Client instance.

    S3Presigner.builder().region(Region.of(BUCKET_REGION))
				.credentialsProvider(awsCredentialProvider).build();

And the way to create awsCredentialProvider is

    AwsBasicCredentials awsBasicCredentials = AwsBasicCredentials.create(SECRET_KEY, ACCESS_KEY);
		return StaticCredentialsProvider.create(awsBasicCredentials);

Collectively:

```
private AwsCredentialsProvider getAwsCredentialProvider() {
	AwsBasicCredentials awsBasicCredentials = AwsBasicCredentials.create(SECRET_KEY, ACCESS_KEY);
	return StaticCredentialsProvider.create(awsBasicCredentials);
}

public S3Presigner buildS3PresignerInstance(AwsCredentialsProvider awsCredentialProvider) {
	return S3Presigner.builder().region(Region.of(BUCKET_REGION))
                      .credentialsProvider(awsCredentialProvider).build();
}
```

